<subSubSection lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,1904,2037]" lastBlockId="9.[151,1436,151,500]" lastPageId="9" lastPageNumber="10" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,275,1904,1929]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Shell small to large, turriform, with elevated spire and short siphonal canal. Subsutural ramp normally well pronounced. Protoconch paucispiral. Shell sculpture pronounced, with axial ribs present at least on spire whorls, and spiral cords, some of which form knobs at their intersection with axial ribs. Columella sometimes with weak plaits. Operculum present or absent, when present with terminal nucleus. Radula with three teeth in a row; rachidian multicuspid; lateral teeth with very long narrow base and two small cusps closer to tip. Proboscis medium-long to long. Paired salivary glands, very large gland of Leiblein, well defined valve of Leiblein. Stomach without caecum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,151,500]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,260,284]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Remarks:</emphasis>
Shells of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. Fischer" authorityYear="1883" box="[430,542,260,284]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[430,542,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Belomitra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[557,664,260,284]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 3" captionStart-1="FIGURE 4" captionStartId-0="10.[151,250,1783,1806]" captionStartId-1="11.[151,250,1451,1474]" captionTargetBox-0="[151,1436,177,1762]" captionTargetBox-1="[151,1434,157,1431]" captionTargetId-0="figure-173@10.[151,1436,159,1762]" captionTargetId-1="figure-227@11.[149,1434,157,1431]" captionTargetPageId-0="10" captionTargetPageId-1="11" captionText-0="FIGURE 3. Type specimens of nominal species of Belomitra. A. Belomitra quadruplex (Watson, 1882), holotype, SL 45 mm (from original description). B–C. Belomitra spelta Locard, 1897, syntype, MNHN, SL 17.4 mm. D. Belomitra torquata (Barnard, 1963), holotype, SL 14.6 mm (after Bouchet &amp; Warén, 1986). E. Belomitra problematica (Thiele, 1925), SL 17.6 mm (from original description). F–G. Belomitra climacella (Dall, 1895), lectotype (here designated), SL 18.8 mm. H–I. Belomitra aikeni (Lussi, 2011); holotype, SL 24.6 mm (H); paratype 1, SL 25.0 mm (I). J. Belomitra viridis (Okutani, 1966). K–M. Belomitra aoteana (Dell, 1956); holotype of Waipaoa munida Ponder, 1968, SL 14.4 mm (after Bouchet &amp; Warén, 1986) (K); holotype of Antizafra aoteana Dell, 1956, SL 10.2 mm (after Bouchet &amp; Warén, 1986) (L); New Zealand, South Island, 45°51.7'S, 171°00.9'E, 340–620 m (NMNZ M.302822), SL 11.2 mm (M). Shells not to scale." captionText-1="FIGURE 4. A–G. Type specimens of nominal species of Belomitra from the Indo-Pacific. A–B. Belomitra leobrerorum Poppe &amp; Tagaro, 2010, holotype, SL 36.5 mm. C–E. Belomitra pacifica (Dall, 1908), holotype, SL 23.1 mm. F–G. Belomitra challengeri (E. A. Smith, 1891), syntype, SL 13.4 mm. H–J. Shells of Conoidea and Mitridae superficially resembling Belomitra. H. Rocroithys niveus Sysoev &amp; Bouchet, 2001, holotype, Vanuatu, SL 25.5 mm (Raphitomidae). I. Raphitomidae gen. sp., Solomon Islands, SL 18.5 mm. J. Charitodoron sp., Mozambique Channel, SL 18.4 mm. Shells not to scale." pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Figs. 3–4</figureCitation>
) superficially resemble those in several other neogastropod families, notably 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bellardi" authorityYear="1875" box="[244,401,295,319]" class="Gastropoda" family="Raphitomidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Raphitomidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Swainson" authorityYear="1831" box="[459,555,295,319]" class="Gastropoda" family="Mitridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Mitridae</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[573,690,295,319]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,250,1451,1474]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,157,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-227@11.[149,1434,157,1431]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 4. A–G. Type specimens of nominal species of Belomitra from the Indo-Pacific. A–B. Belomitra leobrerorum Poppe &amp; Tagaro, 2010, holotype, SL 36.5 mm. C–E. Belomitra pacifica (Dall, 1908), holotype, SL 23.1 mm. F–G. Belomitra challengeri (E. A. Smith, 1891), syntype, SL 13.4 mm. H–J. Shells of Conoidea and Mitridae superficially resembling Belomitra. H. Rocroithys niveus Sysoev &amp; Bouchet, 2001, holotype, Vanuatu, SL 25.5 mm (Raphitomidae). I. Raphitomidae gen. sp., Solomon Islands, SL 18.5 mm. J. Charitodoron sp., Mozambique Channel, SL 18.4 mm. Shells not to scale." pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Fig. 4H–J</figureCitation>
). Among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rafinesque" authorityYear="1815" box="[804,947,295,319]" class="Gastropoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="9" phylum="Mollusca" rank="superFamily" superFamily="Buccinoidea">Buccinoidea</taxonomicName>
, no genus has a shell similar enough to be confused with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="P. Fischer" authorityYear="1883" box="[329,441,332,356]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[329,441,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Belomitra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The shape of the lateral teeth of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[872,1021,332,356]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Belomitridae</taxonomicName>
, with their very long bases, bears resemblance to that in some species of Prosiphonini Powell, 1951, an endemic Antarctic buccinid tribe, the shells of which however can be readily distinguished by being generally much smaller (usually less than 
<quantity box="[1320,1403,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
in length), lacking a defined subsutural ramp, and being sculptured with fewer, dominating strong cords and a lack of pronounced axial elements.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
